{"questionId":"9075213","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The Schwarzschild radius of a black hole is 6.0&nbsp;x 10<sup>5</sup> m. A rocket is 7.0&nbsp;x 10<sup>8</sup> m from the&nbsp;black hole and has a clock. The proper time interval between the ticks of the clock on&nbsp;the rocket is 1.0 s. These ticks are transmitted to a distant observer in a region free of&nbsp;gravitational fields.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Calculate the number of ticks detected in 10 ks by the distant observer.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><em><strong>ALTERNATIVE 1 (10 ks is in observer frame):</strong></em></p>\n<p>Δ<em>t'</em> =&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"10000\\sqrt {1 - \\frac{{6.0 \\times {{10}^5}}}{{7.0 \\times {{10}^8}}}} \">\n  <mn>10000</mn>\n  <msqrt>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n    <mo>−</mo>\n    <mfrac>\n      <mrow>\n        <mn>6.0</mn>\n        <mo>×</mo>\n        <mrow>\n          <msup>\n            <mrow>\n              <mn>10</mn>\n            </mrow>\n            <mn>5</mn>\n          </msup>\n        </mrow>\n      </mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mn>7.0</mn>\n        <mo>×</mo>\n        <mrow>\n          <msup>\n            <mrow>\n              <mn>10</mn>\n            </mrow>\n            <mn>8</mn>\n          </msup>\n        </mrow>\n      </mrow>\n    </mfrac>\n  </msqrt>\n</math></span></p>\n<p>9995.7 so 9995 «ticks»</p>\n<p><em>Allow 9996</em></p>\n<p><em>Allow ECF if 10 is used instead of 1000</em>0</p>\n<p><em><strong>ALTERNATIVE 2 (10 ks is in rocket frame):</strong></em></p>\n<p>Δ<em>t</em>&nbsp;=&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{10000}}{{\\sqrt {1 - \\frac{{6.0 \\times {{10}^5}}}{{7.0 \\times {{10}^8}}}} }}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>10000</mn>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <msqrt>\n        <mn>1</mn>\n        <mo>−</mo>\n        <mfrac>\n          <mrow>\n            <mn>6.0</mn>\n            <mo>×</mo>\n            <mrow>\n              <msup>\n                <mrow>\n                  <mn>10</mn>\n                </mrow>\n                <mn>5</mn>\n              </msup>\n            </mrow>\n          </mrow>\n          <mrow>\n            <mn>7.0</mn>\n            <mo>×</mo>\n            <mrow>\n              <msup>\n                <mrow>\n                  <mn>10</mn>\n                </mrow>\n                <mn>8</mn>\n              </msup>\n            </mrow>\n          </mrow>\n        </mfrac>\n      </msqrt>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span></p>\n<p>10004 «ticks»</p>\n<p><em>Allow ECF if 10 is used instead of 10000</em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9075213","referenceCode":"17N.3.HL.TZ0.b","subjectId":"46-dp-physics-last-assessment-2024","title":"Calculate the number of ticks detected in 10 ks by the distant observer.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Option A: Relativity","Option A: Relativity","Option A: Relativity (Additional higher level option topics)","A.5 – General relativity (HL only)","Option A: Relativity","Option A: Relativity (Additional higher level option topics)"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}